1
00:00:09,141 --> 00:00:13,545
Someday, I will die.

2
00:00:13,546 --> 00:00:15,246
But should I?

3
00:00:15,247 --> 00:00:16,648
If I was offered
a longer life,

4
00:00:16,649 --> 00:00:18,817
I would take that
in a second.

5
00:00:18,818 --> 00:00:21,719
But how long is too long?

6
00:00:21,720 --> 00:00:26,124
Is death something
I should deny forever,

7
00:00:26,125 --> 00:00:30,295
or is death and the role
it plays in the universe

8
00:00:30,296 --> 00:00:56,321
something I am better off
accepting?

9
00:00:56,322 --> 00:00:58,289
I want to start by looking
at a particular way

10
00:00:58,290 --> 00:01:03,495
death affects how we live
and treat one another.

11
00:01:03,496 --> 00:01:05,430
Terror Management Theory

12
00:01:05,431 --> 00:01:07,732
proposes that people
like you and me

13
00:01:07,733 --> 00:01:11,536
manage the terror
of death's inevitability

14
00:01:11,537 --> 00:01:13,805
by embracing cultural values.

15
00:01:13,806 --> 00:01:17,809
That the more aware a person is
of their own mortality,

16
00:01:17,810 --> 00:01:19,477
the more vehemently
they will enforce

17
00:01:19,478 --> 00:01:22,647
their particular views
of the world onto others.

18
00:01:22,648 --> 00:01:25,450
Created by social psychologists
 Sheldon Solomon,

19
00:01:25,451 --> 00:01:27,752
 Jeff Greenberg
 and Tom Pyszczynski,

20
00:01:27,753 --> 00:01:30,755
 Terror Management Theory,
 or TMT,

21
00:01:30,756 --> 00:01:34,392
 suggests that, often,
 we are afraid of change

22
00:01:34,393 --> 00:01:36,728
 because we're afraid
 of death.

23
00:01:36,729 --> 00:01:38,363
 Each one of us
 has a worldview,

24
00:01:38,364 --> 00:01:39,898
 a set of beliefs,
 customs and norms

25
00:01:39,899 --> 00:01:42,667
 we identify with
 that can live on

26
00:01:42,668 --> 00:01:44,802
after our physical bodies die.

27
00:01:44,803 --> 00:01:48,239
 TMT suggest that rises
 in nationalism and prejudice

28
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:52,577
 are correlated with rises
 in the salience of mortality.

29
00:01:52,578 --> 00:01:54,646
 That is, how present
 the inevitability of death is

30
00:01:54,647 --> 00:01:56,247
 in people's minds.

31
00:01:56,248 --> 00:01:58,783
Now this role that death plays
 fascinates me,

32
00:01:58,784 --> 00:02:01,719
 and two of TMT's originators,
 Jeff and Sheldon,

33
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:03,454
 have agreed to work with me
 on a pilot study

34
00:02:03,455 --> 00:02:05,590
 of Terror Management Theory

35
00:02:05,591 --> 00:02:10,294
 and real-life reminders
 of death.

36
00:02:10,295 --> 00:02:12,964
What's your hypothesis today?

37
00:02:12,965 --> 00:02:16,834
Well, I think we're going
to hope for the participants

38
00:02:16,835 --> 00:02:19,204
who are reminded
of their mortality

39
00:02:19,205 --> 00:02:22,874
to be more punitive
in their assessments.

40
00:02:22,875 --> 00:02:25,543
See what happens.

41
00:02:25,544 --> 00:02:26,844
 For our study,

42
00:02:26,845 --> 00:02:29,380
 we created a fake research
 center,

43
00:02:29,381 --> 00:02:30,782
 staffed by actors,

44
00:02:30,783 --> 00:02:32,650
 and invited participants
 to be a part

45
00:02:32,651 --> 00:02:34,452
 of what they were told
 was a focus group

46
00:02:34,453 --> 00:02:36,588
 about the criminal justice
 system.

47
00:02:36,589 --> 00:02:39,557
 During the actual study,
 each group will hear a list

48
00:02:39,558 --> 00:02:41,693
 of several different crimes
 that have been committed,

49
00:02:41,694 --> 00:02:44,762
 and will then be asked
 to propose a punishment

50
00:02:44,763 --> 00:02:46,664
 for each offender
 with a severity level

51
00:02:46,665 --> 00:02:50,468
 ranging from 1 to 7,
 with 1 being the most lenient

52
00:02:50,469 --> 00:02:52,604
 and 7 being
 the most severe.

53
00:02:52,605 --> 00:02:55,473
 The control group will simply
 enter the survey room

54
00:02:55,474 --> 00:02:57,875
 and be asked
 to answer the questions.

55
00:02:57,876 --> 00:02:59,444
 The experimental group,
 however,

56
00:02:59,445 --> 00:03:00,845
 will first be exposed

57
00:03:00,846 --> 00:03:03,348
 to reminders of their own
 mortality

58
00:03:03,349 --> 00:03:06,918
 with strategically placed
 posters in the lobby.

59
00:03:06,919 --> 00:03:08,519
 Also, the questionnaires
 they fill out

60
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:11,522
 will include questions
 about their own death.

61
00:03:11,523 --> 00:03:14,459
 Decades of TMT research
have shown that when presented

62
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:16,427
 with violations
 of common worldviews,

63
00:03:16,428 --> 00:03:19,397
 those who are more aware
 of their own deaths

64
00:03:19,398 --> 00:03:20,665
 will recommend bigger
 punishments

65
00:03:20,666 --> 00:03:22,834
 for the crimes presented.

66
00:03:22,835 --> 00:03:25,303
 But will our real life
 reminders of death,

67
00:03:25,304 --> 00:03:26,804
 not just the survey questions
 usually used,

68
00:03:26,805 --> 00:03:28,706
 make a difference?

69
00:03:28,707 --> 00:03:32,443
 Well, first, let's look
 at the control participants.

70
00:03:32,444 --> 00:03:34,879
[woman] Well, thank you
so much for being here.

71
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:36,381
Now, I cannot
emphasize this enough.

72
00:03:36,382 --> 00:03:38,516
There are no
right or wrong answers.

73
00:03:38,517 --> 00:03:41,486
This is just about
your gut-level reactions.

74
00:03:41,487 --> 00:03:44,489
All right, let's begin.

75
00:03:44,490 --> 00:03:47,025
After raising millions
of dollars in grant money

76
00:03:47,026 --> 00:03:49,460
to fund education
for needy children,

77
00:03:49,461 --> 00:03:51,796
a fundraising manager
unhappy with this life

78
00:03:51,797 --> 00:03:53,364
fled with all the money

79
00:03:53,365 --> 00:03:55,800
and was arrested months later
in Tasmania,

80
00:03:55,801 --> 00:03:57,969
where he was living
under a different name.

81
00:03:57,970 --> 00:04:01,472
So, 1, least punishment:
three months in prison;

82
00:04:01,473 --> 00:04:04,642
7 is most severe:
ten years in prison.

83
00:04:04,643 --> 00:04:09,881
Please answer now.

84
00:04:09,882 --> 00:04:17,554
This is one that I think does
have worldviews on both sides.

85
00:04:17,555 --> 00:04:19,390
[Michael]
 That is a lot of 7s.

86
00:04:19,391 --> 00:04:22,360
 If our control group is
 already maxing out like that,

87
00:04:22,361 --> 00:04:24,629
 well, then our scale
 has no room in that direction

88
00:04:24,630 --> 00:04:27,065
 to show any effect
 of mortality salience.

89
00:04:27,066 --> 00:04:30,368
 Discovering issues like this,
learning how to better isolate

90
00:04:30,369 --> 00:04:32,103
 mortality salience's effect,

91
00:04:32,104 --> 00:04:34,405
 is exactly what a pilot test
 is for.

92
00:04:34,406 --> 00:04:37,775
Hey, personal differences, huh?

93
