173
00:08:43,989 --> 00:08:45,656
[woman]
Okay, thank you so much.

174
00:08:45,657 --> 00:08:47,758
We've finished with this part
of the study.

175
00:08:47,759 --> 00:08:49,594
So if you won't mind
hanging out for a moment,

176
00:08:49,595 --> 00:08:51,262
and our researchers
will be in here in a moment

177
00:08:51,263 --> 00:08:53,297
to ask you a couple questions.

178
00:08:53,298 --> 00:08:56,067
[Michael] Let's find out
 if the reminders of mortality

179
00:08:56,068 --> 00:08:58,836
 we showed our experimental
 group were salient enough.

180
00:08:58,837 --> 00:09:00,204
[Jeff]
Let me ask you about one thing.

181
00:09:00,205 --> 00:09:01,739
Out in the waiting room,

182
00:09:01,740 --> 00:09:04,208
did you all notice
the posters at all?

183
00:09:04,209 --> 00:09:06,711
[woman]
Yes, they are all death-related.

184
00:09:06,712 --> 00:09:11,382
Okay. All right.

185
00:09:11,383 --> 00:09:14,919
Yeah.

186
00:09:14,920 --> 00:09:16,120
-That's right.
-[all laugh]

187
00:09:16,121 --> 00:09:18,623
So we are looking into

188
00:09:18,624 --> 00:09:21,692
something that's called
Terror Management Theory.

189
00:09:21,693 --> 00:09:25,363
And it's the idea that your own
awareness of your mortality

190
00:09:25,364 --> 00:09:29,834
can affect the behaviors
that you exhibit.

191
00:09:29,835 --> 00:09:31,836
That we all manage the terror
that we feel

192
00:09:31,837 --> 00:09:36,207
knowing that we are mortal,
by behaving in certain ways,

193
00:09:36,208 --> 00:09:38,175
especially in ways that
reinforce our own worldviews.

194
00:09:38,176 --> 00:09:41,212
Because we could kind of live on
through the societies

195
00:09:41,213 --> 00:09:43,414
and cultures and identities
that we have today.

196
00:09:43,415 --> 00:09:45,683
[Jeff] Did any of you feel like
you were still thinking

197
00:09:45,684 --> 00:09:48,819
a little bit about death
when you came in here?

198
00:09:48,820 --> 00:09:52,056
I was definitely going
after people who transgressed

199
00:09:52,057 --> 00:09:53,958
against my worldview,
to use your term.

200
00:09:53,959 --> 00:09:57,194
-Yes, I noticed that.
-I was definitely doing that.

201
00:09:57,195 --> 00:09:58,963
[Michael]
So this was incredibly helpful.

202
00:09:58,964 --> 00:10:00,731
-[Jeff] Yeah.
-[Michael] Thank you very much.

203
00:10:00,732 --> 00:10:03,034
[Jeff] Thanks so much.
I appreciate.

204
00:10:03,035 --> 00:10:05,803
[Michael]
It looks like our experimental
 stimuli were successful.

205
00:10:05,804 --> 00:10:07,738
 They were salient, but didn't
 cause the participants

206
00:10:07,739 --> 00:10:09,774
 to think they were related
