209
00:10:18,316 --> 00:10:20,217
if we round up.

210
00:10:20,218 --> 00:10:24,055
So there's a slight tendency
for the experimental people

211
00:10:24,056 --> 00:10:27,925
to be leaning in the direction
that we predicted.

212
00:10:27,926 --> 00:10:29,226
But we're talking about

213
00:10:29,227 --> 00:10:31,896
relatively inconsequential
differences.

214
00:10:31,897 --> 00:10:34,031
That's right. It just makes me
hungry to run more people.

215
00:10:34,032 --> 00:10:35,366
And with the number that we had,

216
00:10:35,367 --> 00:10:37,868
that's statistically
insignificant.

217
00:10:37,869 --> 00:10:40,805
Do you think that we did
see any effects

218
00:10:40,806 --> 00:10:42,940
of mortality salience today?

219
00:10:42,941 --> 00:10:45,209
[Jeff] I feel like the mortality
salient groups

220
00:10:45,210 --> 00:10:47,111
tended to think a little
longer before responding.

221
00:10:47,112 --> 00:10:48,345
Yeah, me too.

222
00:10:48,346 --> 00:10:50,047
[Jeff]
And they seemed more thoughtful.

223
00:10:50,048 --> 00:10:51,982
-They were really--
-They put more effort into it,

224
00:10:51,983 --> 00:10:53,784
into trying to do
the right thing.

225
00:10:53,785 --> 00:10:56,187
The difference was dramatic
enough that we picked up on it.

226
00:10:56,188 --> 00:10:58,789
-Absolutely.
 -Although our stimuli

227
00:10:58,790 --> 00:11:00,925
 might need to go through
 more passes and more vetting,

228
00:11:00,926 --> 00:11:02,293
 we did find
 an interesting difference

229
00:11:02,294 --> 00:11:03,494
 in the time it took

230
