253
00:11:59,017 --> 00:12:01,118
mortality salience
appears to cause,

254
00:12:01,119 --> 00:12:03,154
it also lead
to what looked like

255
00:12:03,155 --> 00:12:06,257
increased consideration
and thought.

256
00:12:06,258 --> 00:12:08,926
I'd love to see more research
on that idea.

257
00:12:08,927 --> 00:12:11,095
But the point is this:

258
00:12:11,096 --> 00:12:15,232
if death's effects
aren't all entirely bad,

259
00:12:15,233 --> 00:12:17,401
what if, instead of,

260
00:12:17,402 --> 00:12:19,970
or at least at the same time

261
00:12:19,971 --> 00:12:22,840
that we hope for the abolition
of natural death,

262
00:12:22,841 --> 00:12:26,944
we also find a way
to accept it?

263
00:12:26,945 --> 00:12:31,015
Now, obviously I don't
want to die, at least not soon.

264
00:12:31,016 --> 00:12:33,884
But accepting the inevitability
of my own death

265
00:12:33,885 --> 00:12:38,823
and being less afraid of it
feels powerful and honest.

266
00:12:38,824 --> 00:12:41,025
I'd like to learn
what that looks like.

267
00:12:41,026 --> 00:12:48,432
And I have a friend
who can help.

268
00:12:48,433 --> 00:12:50,568
 I'm paying a visit
 to Caitlin Doughty,

269
00:12:50,569 --> 00:12:54,438
 a mortician, author,
and death positivity activist,

270
00:12:54,439 --> 00:12:56,907
 who has made an entire career
 out of discussing

271
00:12:56,908 --> 00:13:01,078
 the aspects of death that
 most of us prefer to ignore.

272
00:13:01,079 --> 00:13:05,449
What do you say to someone
who comes to you and says,

273
00:13:05,450 --> 00:13:08,552
"I think death is terrifying.
It's...

274
00:13:08,553 --> 00:13:11,088
"so scary and sad

275
00:13:11,089 --> 00:13:14,024
that I'm just here now"?

276
00:13:14,025 --> 00:13:15,893
Is this person dying,
or is this person...?

277
00:13:15,894 --> 00:13:17,862
This person is me
in front of you right now.

278
00:13:17,863 --> 00:13:19,330
This person is you.
Okay, so...

279
00:13:19,331 --> 00:13:21,198
I would tell you
a couple things.

280
00:13:21,199 --> 00:13:26,103
First, you're dealing with
the primal existential quandary

281
00:13:26,104 --> 00:13:27,371
of human existence.

282
00:13:27,372 --> 00:13:30,107
-Yes.
-And you are one of, you know,

283
00:13:30,108 --> 00:13:33,010
the many billions of people
who have felt this.

284
00:13:33,011 --> 00:13:35,312
So you're not alone
in feeling this way.

285
00:13:35,313 --> 00:13:37,548
So we go through life--
We reach a certain age,

286
00:13:37,549 --> 00:13:40,084
and we begin to understand

287
00:13:40,085 --> 00:13:44,221
that someday ourselves
and everyone we love will die.

288
00:13:44,222 --> 00:13:47,958
And that's powerful,
painful knowledge.

289
00:13:47,959 --> 00:13:50,060
And I think from that moment,

290
00:13:50,061 --> 00:13:53,030
We have to start developing
defense mechanisms

291
00:13:53,031 --> 00:13:56,400
to handle that and to integrate
that into our lives.

292
00:13:56,401 --> 00:13:58,335
So, what are those defense
mechanisms?

293
00:13:58,336 --> 00:14:02,439
I think that the more obvious
ones would be having a child,

294
00:14:02,440 --> 00:14:04,975
writing a book,
making a TV show,

295
00:14:04,976 --> 00:14:06,977
creating a legacy
of some kind.

296
00:14:06,978 --> 00:14:09,613
But there's also a more
insidious version,

297
00:14:09,614 --> 00:14:11,515
which is war.

298
00:14:11,516 --> 00:14:13,217
Taking other countries.

299
00:14:13,218 --> 00:14:16,553
Being rich and being okay with
other people being poor.

300
00:14:16,554 --> 00:14:18,289
I think those are all signs
of death denial.

301
00:14:18,290 --> 00:14:19,657
They're all saying,

302
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:21,558
"But I'm okay,
because I have this money,

303
00:14:21,559 --> 00:14:25,496
"or I have this power, or I have
these kind of dark impulses

304
00:14:25,497 --> 00:14:30,501
that allow me to say, at least
I can outrun death in that way."

305
00:14:30,502 --> 00:14:32,169
And, of course,
that's not true.

306
00:14:32,170 --> 00:14:33,604
No one can outrun death.

307
00:14:33,605 --> 00:14:36,473
But you can trick yourself
into believing that.

308
00:14:36,474 --> 00:14:38,075
So how would you
characterize

309
00:14:38,076 --> 00:14:41,011
the Western relationship
to death?

310
00:14:41,012 --> 00:14:43,981
Take America 150 years ago.

311
00:14:43,982 --> 00:14:47,318
If you were my husband
and you died,

312
00:14:47,319 --> 00:14:49,453
I would be entirely
in charge of you.

313
00:14:49,454 --> 00:14:51,121
I would wash your body.

314
00:14:51,122 --> 00:14:54,224
I would get the neighbor
to make a wooden coffin for you.

315
00:14:54,225 --> 00:14:57,628
We would put you in the coffin
and carry you on our shoulders,

316
00:14:57,629 --> 00:14:59,663
to the grave which someone
had dug themselves.

317
00:14:59,664 --> 00:15:01,298
-Right.
-It would have been

318
00:15:01,299 --> 00:15:03,701
an entirely self-sufficient
process.

319
00:15:03,702 --> 00:15:07,071
But what happened around
the turn of the 20th century

320
00:15:07,072 --> 00:15:09,473
is really three big things
in my mind.

321
00:15:09,474 --> 00:15:12,009
One, you had the rise
of hospitals.

322
00:15:12,010 --> 00:15:14,078
So people were no longer
dying at home.

323
00:15:14,079 --> 00:15:15,980
You had the rise
of funeral homes,

324
00:15:15,981 --> 00:15:19,350
which means that we are now
outsourcing our death.

325
00:15:19,351 --> 00:15:21,318
The third one
is slaughterhouses.

326
00:15:21,319 --> 00:15:24,388
So all of a sudden,
all food production

327
00:15:24,389 --> 00:15:27,524
and the killing of animals
is also hidden as well.

328
00:15:27,525 --> 00:15:30,194
And we live in
our suburban houses,

329
00:15:30,195 --> 00:15:32,162
where all those things
are outsourced.

330
00:15:32,163 --> 00:15:36,266
And it's just these layers and
layers of denial around death.

331
00:15:36,267 --> 00:15:40,704
But what does it mean
to accept death?

332
00:15:40,705 --> 00:15:44,241
I don't think that you ever
truly accept death.

333
00:15:44,242 --> 00:15:48,212
But I believe that the movement
toward accepting death

334
00:15:48,213 --> 00:15:51,148
involves really true
self-awareness

335
00:15:51,149 --> 00:15:55,119
about where you're hiding
your fears of death.

336
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:59,023
That's where real awareness
and acceptance can come from.

337
00:15:59,024 --> 00:16:01,225
For me, the thing that's just
such a bummer about death

338
00:16:01,226 --> 00:16:02,526
is that I just am done.

339
00:16:02,527 --> 00:16:04,728
I don't get to continue
learning things

340
00:16:04,729 --> 00:16:07,131
and seeing what happens.

341
00:16:07,132 --> 00:16:10,100
And I'm just not part
of Earth anymore.

342
00:16:10,101 --> 00:16:13,337
Isn't death kind of what gives
you that passion,

343
00:16:13,338 --> 00:16:14,671
when you think about it?

344
00:16:14,672 --> 00:16:16,640
Like, I love learning,
I love ideas.

345
00:16:16,641 --> 00:16:19,610
If you didn't have an end point,
are you going to come in here

346
00:16:19,611 --> 00:16:23,213
with all these cameras and do
the huge amount of legwork

347
00:16:23,214 --> 00:16:26,083
-that creating a show requires?
-No.

348
00:16:26,084 --> 00:16:28,419
No. Right. Because you're like,
"I don't know, maybe I'll do it

349
00:16:28,420 --> 00:16:30,487
200 years from now."

350
00:16:30,488 --> 00:16:33,290
Whereas right now, you're taking
in information left and right,

351
00:16:33,291 --> 00:16:34,591
because you want
to produce content.

352
00:16:34,592 --> 00:16:37,061
You want to produce
exciting things

353
00:16:37,062 --> 00:16:38,629
and share with other people...

354
00:16:38,630 --> 00:16:41,065
-Because this is my one chance.
-This is your one chance.

355
00:16:41,066 --> 00:16:45,202
The passion and the realness
to life comes from an ending.

356
00:16:45,203 --> 00:16:48,105
That's the great gift
that death gives us.

357
00:16:48,106 --> 00:16:51,275
What's an unhealthy relationship
to have to your own mortality?

358
00:16:51,276 --> 00:16:53,444
The pursuit of immortality,

359
00:16:53,445 --> 00:16:55,846
and the pursuit of,
"I will stay alive

360
00:16:55,847 --> 00:16:58,715
until I can upload my brain
into the cloud."

361
00:16:58,716 --> 00:17:00,217
That worries me.

362
00:17:00,218 --> 00:17:01,819
The idea that everyone
is just allowed

363
00:17:01,820 --> 00:17:04,520
to live forever
from here on out

364
00:17:04,521 --> 00:17:06,722
is not environmentally sensible.

365
00:17:06,723 --> 00:17:14,431
It's not-- You know, it's just
not a sensible position to take.

366
00:17:14,432 --> 00:17:16,333
[narrator]
 We are seeing the dawn

367
00:17:16,334 --> 00:17:19,368
 of a new era
 of possibilities unfold

368
00:17:19,369 --> 00:17:21,171
 on planet Earth.

369
00:17:21,172 --> 00:17:24,208
 What will our amazing world
 be like in, say, 80,

370
00:17:24,209 --> 00:17:27,310
 100, or even 200 years
 from now?

371
00:17:27,311 --> 00:17:29,313
 Wouldn't you like
 the possibility

372
00:17:29,314 --> 00:17:31,381
 of finding out?

373
00:17:31,382 --> 00:17:33,417
[Michael]
 To understand why some people

374
00:17:33,418 --> 00:17:35,519
 feel like death shouldn't
 be inevitable,

375
00:17:35,520 --> 00:17:37,521
 I've come to Alcor,

376
00:17:37,522 --> 00:17:40,224
 one of the world's leading
 life extension facilities.

377
00:17:40,225 --> 00:17:42,192
-Linda. Hi, I'm Michael.
-Hi, how are you?

378
00:17:42,193 --> 00:17:44,194
-Great to meet you.
-Nice to meet you too.

379
00:17:44,195 --> 00:17:46,663
-Welcome to Alcor.
-Thank you for having me here.

380
00:17:46,664 --> 00:17:48,665
 I'm meeting Linda Chamberlin,

381
00:17:48,666 --> 00:17:51,602
 who co-founded Alcor
 nearly 46 years ago.

382
00:17:51,603 --> 00:17:53,504
So this facility that we are in
right now

383
00:17:53,505 --> 00:17:57,841
is where you both cryo-preserve
people and store them.

384
00:17:57,842 --> 00:18:02,146
[Linda]
Yes. We have 160 patients.

385
00:18:02,147 --> 00:18:04,481
-Wow.
-And we have

386
00:18:04,482 --> 00:18:08,585
eleven hundred
and ninety-something members.

387
00:18:08,586 --> 00:18:10,420
-It changes.
-And a member is someone

388
00:18:10,421 --> 00:18:12,789
-who is alive today but has...
-Alive today.

389
00:18:12,790 --> 00:18:15,759
They've made the arrangements
for this.

390
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:18,929
Once they are cryo-preserved,
they become patients.

391
00:18:18,930 --> 00:18:20,330
You're using
the word "patient."

392
00:18:20,331 --> 00:18:21,532
-Yes.
-Okay.

393
00:18:21,533 --> 00:18:23,433
Tell me about why you use
that word.

394
00:18:23,434 --> 00:18:27,271
For us, death is not something
which is like an on/off switch.

395
00:18:27,272 --> 00:18:30,207
One second you're alive,
the next second you're dead.

396
00:18:30,208 --> 00:18:32,543
-Mm-hmm.
-What we are trying to do

397
00:18:32,544 --> 00:18:36,446
is to slow down and stop
the dying process.

398
00:18:36,447 --> 00:18:38,348
[Michael]
 To become a patient at Alcor,

399
00:18:38,349 --> 00:18:42,386
 first you have to pay
 between 80 and $200,000

400
00:18:42,387 --> 00:18:44,488
 Then you have to die,

401
00:18:44,489 --> 00:18:48,225
 or more specifically,
be pronounced clinically dead.

402
00:18:48,226 --> 00:18:50,494
 This generally means
 that your heart and lungs

403
00:18:50,495 --> 00:18:51,929
 have stopped functioning.

404
00:18:51,930 --> 00:18:54,531
 At that point,
 Alcor can begin their work.

405
00:18:54,532 --> 00:18:56,867
Now, there are two ways
that a person could sign up

406
00:18:56,868 --> 00:18:58,535
for this procedure.

407
00:18:58,536 --> 00:19:01,972
There's a whole-body patient,
or as a neuro.

408
00:19:01,973 --> 00:19:03,607
Oh, and does "neuro"
just mean head?

409
00:19:03,608 --> 00:19:05,909
It means, yes,
the cephalon, actually,

410
00:19:05,910 --> 00:19:08,745
which is all of the structures
down to about the clavicle.

411
00:19:08,746 --> 00:19:10,781
-Uh-huh.
-I'm a neuro.

412
00:19:10,782 --> 00:19:15,319
Everybody in my family,
who's now in stasis, is a neuro.

413
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:16,720
-Really?
-Most of the people

414
00:19:16,721 --> 00:19:21,358
who really understand
the technology are neuros.

415
00:19:21,359 --> 00:19:25,629
The primary reason that people
choose whole body is emotional.

416
00:19:25,630 --> 00:19:28,232
-Of course.
-And they're not comfortable

417
00:19:28,233 --> 00:19:32,736
with the idea of their body
being removed and discarded.

418
00:19:32,737 --> 00:19:37,274
So let's say that our patient
is whole body.

419
00:19:37,275 --> 00:19:39,643
The moment the patient
is pronounced,

420
00:19:39,644 --> 00:19:41,011
they go into an ice bath.

421
00:19:41,012 --> 00:19:43,347
And this is just crushed ice.

422
00:19:43,348 --> 00:19:45,282
And it's water
in there as well.

423
00:19:45,283 --> 00:19:48,485
Their heart has started again
with a mechanical thumper.

424
00:19:48,486 --> 00:19:51,888
They're intubated, and their
lungs are functioning again.

425
00:19:51,889 --> 00:19:53,390
Being ventilated.

426
00:19:53,391 --> 00:19:55,759
Circulating the cooler
temperatures.

427
00:19:55,760 --> 00:19:57,761
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
So you need the veins,

428
00:19:57,762 --> 00:19:59,563
the arteries,
the vasculature, the heart.

429
00:19:59,564 --> 00:20:03,567
You need all of those continuing
to pump and circulate.

430
00:20:03,568 --> 00:20:05,736
[Linda]
This is our operating room.

431
00:20:05,737 --> 00:20:06,937
[Michael]
Wow.

432
00:20:06,938 --> 00:20:08,672
So basically,

433
00:20:08,673 --> 00:20:11,808
when the patient comes in
through the door there,

434
00:20:11,809 --> 00:20:16,346
they'll go into this specially
developed operating table.

435
00:20:16,347 --> 00:20:21,818
It is going to be circulating
nitrogen gas over them

436
00:20:21,819 --> 00:20:24,021
to help cool them externally.

437
00:20:24,022 --> 00:20:26,490
And if it's a whole-body
patient,

438
00:20:26,491 --> 00:20:29,760
then the surgeons
open the chest,

439
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:33,630
and then we begin circulating
the organ transplant solution.

440
00:20:33,631 --> 00:20:35,699
[Michael]
 Once in the operating room,

441
00:20:35,700 --> 00:20:37,301
 the patient's blood
 is replaced

442
00:20:37,302 --> 00:20:39,503
 with cooled organ
 transplant fluid

443
00:20:39,504 --> 00:20:41,672
 and circulated
 through the vascular system

444
00:20:41,673 --> 00:20:43,507
 to rapidly cool down
 the internal

445
00:20:43,508 --> 00:20:45,475
 and external temperatures
 of the body.

446
00:20:45,476 --> 00:20:47,744
 Just before the water
 within the body tissue

447
00:20:47,745 --> 00:20:49,546
 reaches its freezing point,

448
00:20:49,547 --> 00:20:52,049
 cryo-protective fluids
 are introduced.

449
00:20:52,050 --> 00:20:53,984
 These act like antifreeze,

450
00:20:53,985 --> 00:20:55,986
 preventing the formation
 of ice crystals

451
00:20:55,987 --> 00:20:58,422
 that could damage
 soft tissue.

452
00:20:58,423 --> 00:21:01,758
 This is called
 the vitrification process.

453
00:21:01,759 --> 00:21:04,328
Now, say that it is
a neuro patient.

454
00:21:04,329 --> 00:21:07,531
-So they come in first here.
-Yup, their whole body.

455
00:21:07,532 --> 00:21:10,701
Right. The surgeons will do
the neuro separation first.

456
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:12,903
-Okay, yeah, that makes sense.
-Separate the cephalon,

457
00:21:12,904 --> 00:21:16,073
which is all of the structures
down to about the clavicle.

458
00:21:16,074 --> 00:21:18,942
Bring it over here

459
00:21:18,943 --> 00:21:24,348
to this operating field.

460
00:21:24,349 --> 00:21:25,882
We'll wash the blood out.

461
00:21:25,883 --> 00:21:29,086
And we introduce the organ
transplant solution.

462
00:21:29,087 --> 00:21:32,889
I'm imagining
a person's cephalon,

463
00:21:32,890 --> 00:21:34,591
essentially their head,
in here.

464
00:21:34,592 --> 00:21:36,760
I can see how it's going
to get clamped in.

465
00:21:36,761 --> 00:21:38,128
[Linda]
Yeah.

466
00:21:38,129 --> 00:21:40,731
[Michael]
That looks like, I'm sure,

467
00:21:40,732 --> 00:21:42,666
a crazy sci-fi movie.

468
00:21:42,667 --> 00:21:45,635
-But it really happens.
-It really happens.

469
00:21:45,636 --> 00:21:47,871
[Michael]
After the vitrification process
 is complete,

470
00:21:47,872 --> 00:21:49,973
 the patients are placed
 inside bags

471
00:21:49,974 --> 00:21:52,442
 that are attached
 to open metal cases,

472
00:21:52,443 --> 00:21:54,644
 which are then placed inside
 cylindrical tanks

473
00:21:54,645 --> 00:21:58,048
 filled with liquid nitrogen,
 called dewars.

474
00:21:58,049 --> 00:22:00,083
So this is our
patient care bay.

475
00:22:00,084 --> 00:22:02,152
We have 159 patients.

476
00:22:02,153 --> 00:22:05,155
-In these tanks right here?
-In these tanks.

477
00:22:05,156 --> 00:22:08,992
There are approximately

478
00:22:08,993 --> 00:22:11,161
nine patients
in each one of these.

479
00:22:11,162 --> 00:22:14,831
Four whole bodies
and five neuros.

480
00:22:14,832 --> 00:22:17,901
This one right here

481
00:22:17,902 --> 00:22:21,571
is where my husband
is currently housed.

482
00:22:21,572 --> 00:22:23,039
-This one right here?
-Right.

483
00:22:23,040 --> 00:22:25,142
This is where Fred is
at the moment.

484
00:22:25,143 --> 00:22:29,479
My mother and my father-in-law
are...

485
00:22:29,480 --> 00:22:30,814
in this one.

486
00:22:30,815 --> 00:22:32,949
[Michael]
Wow, it's so weird,

487
00:22:32,950 --> 00:22:37,721
because I am right now
not in a graveyard.

488
00:22:37,722 --> 00:22:42,058
No. Alcor is very much
like an ambulance

489
00:22:42,059 --> 00:22:44,694
taking their loved ones
to a hospital

490
00:22:44,695 --> 00:22:45,962
not down the street,

491
00:22:45,963 --> 00:22:48,432
-but a hospital in the future.
-Yeah.

492
00:22:48,433 --> 00:22:51,001
When technology
can help them.

493
00:22:51,002 --> 00:22:53,470
They're not being transported
through space,

494
00:22:53,471 --> 00:22:55,605
-but through time.
-Time.

495
00:22:55,606 --> 00:22:59,075
[Michael] To see what drives
this time-traveling ambulance,

496
00:22:59,076 --> 00:23:01,077
 I'm going to sit down
 with Max More,

497
00:23:01,078 --> 00:23:05,816
 Alcor's CEO,
 and a future neuro patient.

498
00:23:05,817 --> 00:23:08,819
So, Max, what's the status
of the technology needed

499
00:23:08,820 --> 00:23:11,788
to revive cryo-preserved
specimens?

500
00:23:11,789 --> 00:23:13,623
-Are we getting closer?
-We are getting closer.

501
00:23:13,624 --> 00:23:14,958
It's going to be decades,
at least,

502
00:23:14,959 --> 00:23:17,794
before we can bring back
whole human beings.

503
00:23:17,795 --> 00:23:21,998
But we already cryo-preserve
eggs, sperm,

504
00:23:21,999 --> 00:23:23,233
microbes of skin, corneas,

505
00:23:23,234 --> 00:23:25,035
heart valves,
all kinds of things.

506
00:23:25,036 --> 00:23:27,471
So those are single tissues.
And we can reverse that process.

507
00:23:27,472 --> 00:23:29,573
-Mm-hmm.
-You move from that to an organ,

508
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:31,007
things get more difficult.

509
00:23:31,008 --> 00:23:34,478
But we actually did an
experiment a few years ago.

510
00:23:34,479 --> 00:23:36,012
We took this little tiny worm.

511
00:23:36,013 --> 00:23:37,881
We used a certain chemical
so we'd learn that,

512
00:23:37,882 --> 00:23:39,816
oh, my food's over here
and not over here.

513
00:23:39,817 --> 00:23:41,117
And we cryo-preserved them.

514
00:23:41,118 --> 00:23:43,520
And then we just waited,
brought them back,

515
00:23:43,521 --> 00:23:45,021
and then we tested them.

516
00:23:45,022 --> 00:23:46,890
We were able to demonstrate
with the memory test

517
00:23:46,891 --> 00:23:48,658
that the ones that have received
the training

518
00:23:48,659 --> 00:23:50,126
retained that memory.

519
00:23:50,127 --> 00:23:51,628
So it was the first time
any organism

520
00:23:51,629 --> 00:23:53,196
we've proven to survive
with memory.

521
00:23:53,197 --> 00:23:55,832
So now we're asking, okay,
what's the next step?

522
00:23:55,833 --> 00:23:58,635
Because whole organisms are
difficult to reverse right now.

523
00:23:58,636 --> 00:24:00,570
But step by step,
the more progress we can make,

524
00:24:00,571 --> 00:24:03,006
-the more convincing this is.
-Wow.

525
00:24:03,007 --> 00:24:04,941
When it comes
to extending life,

526
00:24:04,942 --> 00:24:08,144
some questions come up, like,
