553
00:25:01,966 --> 00:25:05,302
then would they also advocate
people who live to 90

554
00:25:05,303 --> 00:25:06,937
should be killed off at 45?

555
00:25:06,938 --> 00:25:08,738
Will that double the meaning
in their life?

556
00:25:08,739 --> 00:25:11,241
In fact, I think life gets more
meaning the longer you live,

557
00:25:11,242 --> 00:25:13,977
because you can build
on what you've done before.

558
00:25:13,978 --> 00:25:16,112
So if anything, it increases
the meaningfulness of life,

559
00:25:16,113 --> 00:25:17,714
in my view.

560
00:25:17,715 --> 00:25:19,983
You're making me realize
that, in many ways,

561
00:25:19,984 --> 00:25:24,688
I am rationalizing death.

562
00:25:24,689 --> 00:25:27,724
I'm looking for ways
to excuse it and accept it.

563
00:25:27,725 --> 00:25:31,328
I don't think it's unhealthy
to accept that you are mortal.

564
00:25:31,329 --> 00:25:32,762
Well, I have to accept it,

565
00:25:32,763 --> 00:25:34,297
because I could get killed
at any time.

566
00:25:34,298 --> 00:25:35,932
One thing I have to stress,

567
00:25:35,933 --> 00:25:37,701
because every
article written,

568
00:25:37,702 --> 00:25:39,235
they always have to use
the word "forever,"

569
00:25:39,236 --> 00:25:40,837
or "immortality."

570
00:25:40,838 --> 00:25:42,606
And that's not
on the table here.

571
00:25:42,607 --> 00:25:44,374
We're just offering a chance
for people to be revived

572
00:25:44,375 --> 00:25:45,942
when we've beaten aging.

573
00:25:45,943 --> 00:25:47,978
And eventually something's
going to get you.

574
00:25:47,979 --> 00:25:49,813
So we're not offering
immortality.

575
00:25:49,814 --> 00:26:01,958
We're offering an unknown
extension of human lifespan.

576
00:26:01,959 --> 00:26:06,396
Do I think that someday we will
be able to cryonically freeze

577
00:26:06,397 --> 00:26:11,101
an entire person
and then revive them?

578
00:26:11,102 --> 00:26:12,302
Yes, I do.

579
00:26:12,303 --> 00:26:14,070
I believe that
cryopreservation

580
00:26:14,071 --> 00:26:16,706
will change the meaning
of death,

581
00:26:16,707 --> 00:26:19,175
and lead to breakthroughs
in medical technology

582
00:26:19,176 --> 00:26:22,012
that will improve
all of our lives.

583
00:26:22,013 --> 00:26:26,983
But do I want to extend my life
indefinitely?

584
00:26:26,984 --> 00:26:28,852
Well, on the one hand,

585
00:26:28,853 --> 00:26:31,021
obviously death
is a bummer.

586
00:26:31,022 --> 00:26:32,389
But on the other,

587
00:26:32,390 --> 00:26:35,325
the universe managed fine
without me

588
00:26:35,326 --> 00:26:37,727
for billions of years.

589
00:26:37,728 --> 00:26:39,863
Am I really so important

590
00:26:39,864 --> 00:26:42,832
that it should never
not have me again?

591
00:26:42,833 --> 00:26:46,269
Should I be around
as long as possible?

592
00:26:46,270 --> 00:26:51,941
Or do those who will come later
deserve their own world?

593
00:26:51,942 --> 00:26:54,978
Should I try
to extend my life?

594
00:26:54,979 --> 00:26:59,983
Or should I decide to die
when my time comes

595
00:26:59,984 --> 00:27:03,787
and return all this matter
I'm borrowing back to the world?

596
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:06,389
Well, I don't think
there's a right answer.

597
00:27:06,390 --> 00:27:09,693
It's a personal choice
we each get to make,

598
00:27:09,694 --> 00:27:11,394
and should be able to make.

599
00:27:11,395 --> 00:27:18,935
And I've been thinking
about it a lot.

600
00:27:18,936 --> 00:27:21,771
 So I'm going to speak again
 with my friend Caitlin,

601
00:27:21,772 --> 00:27:25,875
 the mortician,
 to confront my own mortality.

602
00:27:25,876 --> 00:27:27,744
Well, Caitlin, thanks for
meeting with me again.

603
00:27:27,745 --> 00:27:29,713
I've been surrounded
